## 3Ô∏è‚É£ Recommended timing budget (safe)

For **100 ¬µs total ON time**, do:

| Phase            | Time         |
| ---------------- | ------------ |
| Power-on         | 0 ¬µs         |
| Settling         | **50‚Äì70 ¬µs** |
| Sample / compare | **10‚Äì20 ¬µs** |
| Power-off        | remainder    |

This leaves little margin ‚Äî so timing must be deterministic.

---

## 4Ô∏è‚É£ How to power-gate the sensor (correctly)

### Best method: **Load switch / PMOS**

Do **not** power the sensor directly from a GPIO.

```
VDD ‚îÄ‚îÄ P-MOSFET ‚îÄ‚îÄ TMR VDD
         ‚Üë
      GPIO
```

* Choose a **low-leakage, low-Rds(on)** PMOS
* Gate pulled high by default ‚Üí OFF in sleep
* GPIO pulls gate low to turn sensor ON

This ensures:
‚úî Clean supply
‚úî No back-powering through I/O
‚úî ¬µA-level leakage when off

---

## 5Ô∏è‚É£ How to time this on nRF54L15 (low power)

### Use **RTC + DPPI** (no CPU jitter)

1. RTC fires every 10 ms
2. DPPI turns on sensor power GPIO
3. RTC compare (after ~70 ¬µs) triggers ADC sample or comparator enable
4. RTC compare (after 100 ¬µs) turns sensor power OFF

This keeps:

* CPU asleep
* Timing deterministic
* Power minimal

---

## 6Ô∏è‚É£ Comparator vs ADC with power-gated sensor

### Comparator

‚ùå Not ideal here

* Comparator needs stable input
* Turning it on/off repeatedly risks false triggers
* Best for *always-on* signals

### ADC (recommended)

‚úî ADC samples at a known instant
‚úî Can discard first sample
‚úî Works well with burst-mode sensing

